It Depends on How Your Pivot Table is Set Up
✅ If your Pivot Table source is a Named Table (ListObject)
Yes — new rows update automatically when you refresh.

In Excel, if your raw data is formatted as a Table (Insert → Table, or Ctrl+T), it looks like this:

![Excel Table with blue striped rows]

The table expands automatically with new rows — pivot table picks it up on refresh. ✅

❌ If your Pivot Table source is a Fixed Range (like A1:Z500)
No — new rows beyond row 500 will be ignored.

This is the most common mistake. Your pivot was probably created pointing to a fixed range like Sheet1!$A$1:$Z$500.

How to Check Which One You Have
Click anywhere inside your Pivot Table → PivotTable Analyze tab → Change Data Source

You'll see either:

Sheet1!$A$1:$Z$500     ← BAD (fixed range, won't grow)
or

Raw_Data[#All]  or  Table1        ← GOOD (dynamic table)
Fix It Once — Works Forever After
Step 1 — Convert your raw data to a Table
Click anywhere in your raw data
Press Ctrl + T → OK
Name it Raw_Data in the top-left Table Name box
Step 2 — Point Pivot to the Table
Click Pivot Table → PivotTable Analyze → Change Data Source
Type Raw_Data (your table name) → OK
Step 3 — VBA refresh handles the rest
Now whenever new rows are pasted, VBA's RefreshAll picks up all new rows automatically — no manual range adjustment ever needed.

